AML Policy

Anti-Money Laundering, Counter-Terrorist Financing and Counter-Proliferation Financing Policy and Procedures Introduction Money laundering is the process by which criminals attempt to conceal the true origin and ownership of the proceeds of criminal activities. Terrorist financing and proliferation financing may involve the raising, movement or use of funds for unlawful purposes regardless of whether those funds derive from criminal conduct. Alamut Investment Management LLP (the “Firm”) is committed to maintaining effective systems and controls to prevent the Firm, the funds it manages, and associated structures from being used for money laundering, terrorist financing, proliferation financing, sanctions evasion or other financial crime. This Policy applies to Alamut Investment Management LLP as the Firm’s only UK regulated entity. The Firm acts as AIFM / investment manager in respect of a Cayman master-feeder structure comprising Alamut Master Fund Ltd, Alamut Feeder Fund Ltd and Alamut Feeder LP (together, the “Funds”). The Firm recognises that, although investor onboarding, screening and ongoing monitoring functions may be delegated operationally to the fund administrator, the Firm must nevertheless maintain systems and controls sufficient to counter the risk that it may be used to further financial crime, including money laundering risk. The FCA has stated that, as an AIFM, a firm must have systems and controls sufficient to counter the risk that the firm is used to further financial crime, including where investor due diligence is performed by third parties. This Policy is intended to support compliance with: 

the Proceeds of Crime Act 2002;



the Terrorism Act 2000;



the Money Laundering, Terrorist Financing and Transfer of Funds (Information on the Payer) Regulations 2017, as amended (the “UK MLRs”);



the FCA’s SYSC and financial crime expectations;



applicable UK financial sanctions requirements; and



to the extent relevant to the Funds and their service providers, applicable Cayman Islands AML / CFT / CPF requirements and guidance.

Policy Statement
The Firm will:
1. identify and assess the money laundering, terrorist financing, proliferation financing and sanctions risks to
which its business is exposed;
2. establish and maintain proportionate policies, controls and procedures to mitigate and manage those
risks;
3. apply a risk-based approach to investor due diligence and ongoing monitoring;
4. oversee any delegated AML functions carried out by the fund administrator or other service providers;
5. escalate and investigate unusual or suspicious activity;
6. make disclosures or reports where required by law;
7. keep appropriate records; and
8. provide AML, sanctions and financial crime training to relevant staff.
Under the UK MLRs, a relevant person must take appropriate steps to identify and assess money laundering and
terrorist financing risk, taking account of customers, geographies, products, transactions and delivery channels,
and must maintain written policies, controls and procedures approved by senior management.

Scope This Policy applies to: 

Alamut Investment Management LLP;



all partners, employees, temporary personnel and secondees of the Firm;



the Firm’s activities in managing and overseeing the Funds; and



the Firm’s oversight of delegated investor AML and sanctions controls operated by the fund administrator and other relevant service providers.

This Policy does not purport to replace the separate legal obligations of the Funds themselves, the fund administrator, or other service providers. Where AML functions are delegated, the Firm remains responsible for its own systems and controls, oversight and escalation framework. That approach is consistent with the MSFS policy, which expressly states that the administrator’s services do not supersede the client’s own responsibilities under applicable AML laws.

Governance and Responsibilities Managing Board / Members The Managing Board / Members are responsible for: 

approving this Policy and any material amendments;



overseeing the Firm’s AML / CFT / CPF framework;



ensuring sufficient resources are available to operate the framework effectively;



reviewing AML reporting, material incidents and remediation; and



promoting a culture of compliance and escalation.

Board Owner A senior member of the Firm shall have overall responsibility for this Policy and for ensuring that it is reviewed, maintained and communicated appropriately.

MLRO The Firm shall appoint an MLRO with responsibility for: 

oversight of the Firm’s AML / CFT / CPF systems and controls;



receiving and assessing internal suspicious activity reports;



determining whether external reporting is required;



liaising with regulators, law enforcement and service providers where necessary;



maintaining AML records, logs and reporting; and



reporting periodically to senior management on the effectiveness of the Firm’s AML framework.

Deputy MLRO The Firm shall appoint a Deputy MLRO to support the MLRO and to act where the MLRO is unavailable.

AMLCO / Compliance The Firm shall maintain appropriate compliance oversight of its AML framework, including: 

periodic review of this Policy;



oversight of delegated AML arrangements;



review of investor onboarding and exception reporting from the fund administrator;



testing and monitoring of controls; and



escalation of deficiencies or unusual matters.

Staff Responsibilities All staff must: 

be alert to money laundering, terrorist financing, proliferation financing and sanctions risks;



comply with this Policy and related procedures;



complete required training;



report concerns promptly to the MLRO or Deputy MLRO; and



avoid tipping off or otherwise prejudicing any investigation.

Risk Based Approach The Firm adopts a risk-based approach to AML / CFT / CPF. The Firm’s business-wide risk assessment shall consider, among other things: 

the nature of the Firm’s activities and the Funds;



investor types and characteristics;



the nature of subscriptions and redemptions;



geographic exposure;



complexity of ownership and control structures;



use of nominees, intermediaries and introducers;



bank account and payment risks;



sanctions exposure;



use of delegated service providers; and



adverse media or other financial crime indicators.

The UK MLRs require risk assessment by reference to customer, geography, product, transaction and delivery channel risk, and require the assessment to be kept up to date and made available to the supervisory authority on request. The Firm’s risk assessment shall be reviewed at least annually and more frequently if there is a material change to the Firm’s business, investor base, fund structure, service providers or risk profile.

Risk Categorisation The Firm categorises relationships and investors, where relevant to its oversight responsibilities, as Low Risk, Medium Risk or High Risk.

Low Risk
Examples may include:
1. appropriately regulated financial institutions in the UK or comparable jurisdictions;
2. public authorities or governmental bodies in lower-risk jurisdictions;
3. listed entities subject to appropriate disclosure requirements; and
4. institutional investors with transparent ownership and a clear regulatory status.
High Risk
Examples may include:
1. politically exposed persons, their family members or close associates;
2. complex or opaque ownership structures;
3. relationships involving high-risk jurisdictions;
4. investors linked to adverse media or prior financial crime concerns;
5. investors involving third-party payments or unexplained payment arrangements;
6. structures that are difficult to understand or verify;
7. sanctioned or potentially sanctioned persons; and
8. relationships identified by the Firm or the administrator as presenting elevated risk.
Medium Risk
All other relationships or investors that do not clearly fall within Low Risk or High Risk categories.

Delegation to Fund Administrator The Firm has appointed Morgan Stanley Fund Services and/or the relevant Morgan Stanley fund administration entity (“MSFS” or the “Administrator”) to provide fund administration services to the Funds, including certain investor AML, onboarding, screening and ongoing monitoring services, in each case subject to the terms of the applicable administration agreement. In line with that arrangement, the Administrator may perform operational AML services including, where applicable: 

collection of subscription documents and investor identification materials;



risk-based identification and verification of investors and relevant associated persons;



sanctions, PEP and adverse media screening;



validation of subscription and redemption account details;



periodic refresh of investor due diligence;



review of exceptions, restrictions and incomplete files; and



escalation of suspicious, restricted or unusual activity.

This drafting reflects the structure of the MSFS sample, which describes onboarding, screening and ongoing monitoring as part of the administrator’s AML services, while making clear that such services are subject to the administration agreement and do not displace the client’s own obligations. The Firm’s position is therefore as follows: 

the Administrator performs the agreed AML services in accordance with the administration agreement and its own applicable legal and regulatory obligations;



the Firm remains responsible for maintaining effective AML systems and controls in respect of its own regulated business and for exercising appropriate oversight over delegated AML functions;



the Firm shall receive and review periodic AML and exception reporting from the Administrator;



material exceptions, overdue CDD, sanctions hits, payment irregularities, account restrictions and suspicious activity concerns must be escalated promptly to the Firm;



the Firm shall conduct initial and periodic due diligence on the Administrator’s AML framework; and



the Firm may require further information, challenge determinations or direct escalation where appropriate.

The FCA’s April 2026 and March 2024 guidance both reinforce the importance of effective investor due diligence, governance, monitoring and oversight where third parties are used. The Firm also recognises that Cayman guidance permits reliance and delegation only where the arrangement is appropriately documented and the relevant financial service provider remains satisfied as to the adequacy of the delegated controls.

Investor Due Diligence The Firm requires that appropriate customer due diligence is carried out in relation to investors in the Funds. IDD is expected to include, as applicable: 

identification of the investor;



verification of the investor’s identity using reliable and independent documents or information;



identification of beneficial owners and persons acting on behalf of the investor where required;



understanding of the ownership and control structure;



screening for sanctions, PEP and adverse media risk;



understanding of the purpose and intended nature of the investment relationship; and



collection of such additional information as is required under the applicable onboarding forms, subscription documents, administration procedures and legal requirements.

Under regulation 28 of the UK MLRs, CDD includes identification and verification of the customer and, where applicable, beneficial owners, together with assessment of the purpose and intended nature of the business relationship. The Firm expects these steps to be carried out by the Administrator in accordance with the administration agreement, the Funds’ onboarding documentation and applicable law, subject to the Firm’s oversight.

Simplified Due Diligence Simplified due diligence may be applied only where permitted by applicable law and where the relevant relationship presents a demonstrably low degree of risk. Any use of simplified due diligence must be justified on a documented risk-based basis and be consistent with the applicable onboarding procedures and legal requirements.

Enhanced Due Diligence Enhanced due diligence shall be applied where required by law or where the risk profile of the investor or relationship warrants it. EDD may include: 

obtaining additional identification and verification materials;



enhanced scrutiny of ownership and control;



source of funds enquiries;



source of wealth enquiries where appropriate;



senior management approval;



enhanced review of adverse media and reputational issues;



enhanced scrutiny of payment arrangements; and



increased frequency of ongoing monitoring.

The UK MLRs require enhanced due diligence and enhanced ongoing monitoring in higher-risk cases.

Beneficial Ownership and Control For legal entity investors, the Firm expects the Administrator to identify and verify beneficial ownership and control information to the extent required by the applicable subscription documents, onboarding procedures and law. The Firm does not prescribe a rigid threshold in this Policy, but requires that the relevant standards reflected in the Funds’ investor onboarding documentation and applicable legal requirements are followed.

Where ownership, control or authority to act cannot be properly understood or verified, the matter must be escalated and the relationship should not proceed until satisfactorily resolved.

Politically Exposed Persons Investors or related persons identified as PEPs, or as family members or close associates of PEPs, must be treated as presenting heightened risk and be subject to EDD. This will ordinarily include: 

identification through screening and/or investor disclosure;



escalation to senior management;



appropriate source of funds and, where relevant, source of wealth review; and



enhanced ongoing monitoring.

This approach is consistent with both the sample AIFM policy and current UK requirements.

Sanctions and Proliferation Financing The Firm shall maintain controls designed to identify and prevent dealings involving sanctioned persons, restricted parties, embargoed territories or prohibited transactions. These controls shall include, to the extent relevant: 

sanctions screening of investors and associated parties;



screening of payment instructions and account details where applicable;



escalation of actual or potential sanctions matches;



restrictions, blocking or rejection of activity where required; and



consideration of proliferation financing risk in the Firm’s business-wide risk assessment and controls.

Cayman’s 2024 Guidance Notes expressly cover money laundering, terrorist financing and proliferation financing.

Ongoing Monitoring The Firm requires ongoing monitoring of investor relationships and related activity on a risk-sensitive basis. This may include: 

periodic refresh of due diligence records;



review of changes in investor ownership or control;



review of changes to authorised signatories or bank account details;



scrutiny of subscription and redemption patterns;



review of early or unusual redemptions;



monitoring for third-party payments;



ongoing sanctions, PEP and adverse media screening; and



review of administrator exceptions and restrictions.

This aligns with the operational themes set out in the MSFS policy, including periodic refresh, sanctions screening, review of redemptions and monitoring for third-party payments and unusual activity.

Third-Party Payments and Bank Account Controls The Firm expects subscriptions to be received from, and redemptions to be paid to, accounts appropriately linked to the relevant investor, save where an exception is permitted under applicable law, Fund procedures and the Administrator’s controls. Any proposed or actual third-party payment arrangement, discrepancy between investor and bank account holder names, or unexplained change in payment instructions must be subject to additional review and escalation.

Suspicious Activity Reporting Any person within the Firm who knows, suspects, or has reasonable grounds to suspect money laundering, terrorist financing, proliferation financing, sanctions evasion or related financial crime must report the matter promptly to the MLRO or Deputy MLRO. The MLRO shall determine whether an external suspicious activity report should be submitted to the UK Financial Intelligence Unit. The National Crime Agency states that SARs alert law enforcement to suspected money laundering or terrorist financing and should be submitted through the SAR Portal. No member of staff may tip off, or otherwise disclose, that a report has been made or is contemplated, except as permitted by law. Where a suspicious activity concern arises from Administrator monitoring, the Firm expects immediate escalation from the Administrator in accordance with the administration agreement and agreed escalation procedures.

Refusal, Restriction and Termination The Firm, in conjunction with the Administrator and the governing body of the relevant Fund where necessary, may decline to onboard an investor, restrict an account, suspend processing, reject a subscription, delay a redemption or terminate a relationship where:



required due diligence is incomplete or unsatisfactory;



sanctions concerns arise;



suspicious activity concerns remain unresolved;



source of funds or source of wealth information is inadequate;



ownership or control cannot be satisfactorily understood; or



the relationship falls outside the Firm’s risk appetite.

Record Keeping The Firm shall maintain appropriate AML records, whether held directly by the Firm or by the Administrator on the Funds’ behalf. These records may include: 

the business-wide risk assessment;



this Policy and related procedures;



investor due diligence and screening records;



escalations and approvals;



suspicious activity logs;



training records;



oversight records relating to the Administrator; and



periodic AML reporting.

Under regulation 40 of the UK MLRs, relevant persons must keep CDD records and supporting transaction records for the applicable retention period. Where records are maintained by the Administrator, the Firm must remain able to obtain them promptly.

Training The Firm shall provide appropriate AML / CFT / CPF and sanctions training to relevant staff on induction and at least annually thereafter. Training shall cover: 

the Firm’s legal and regulatory obligations;



the content of this Policy;



fund-specific money laundering risk indicators;



suspicious activity escalation;



sanctions and proliferation financing risk;



delegated oversight responsibilities; and



anti-tipping off obligations.

Regulation 21 of the UK MLRs requires, where appropriate having regard to the size and nature of the business, internal controls including screening of employees, an independent audit function and training.

Independent Review and Audit The Firm shall ensure that its AML framework is subject to periodic independent review, whether internally or externally, to assess whether controls remain appropriate and effective. This review may include: 

the business-wide risk assessment;



operation of this Policy;



oversight of delegated arrangements;



exception management;



suspicious activity escalation;



record-keeping; and



remediation of identified deficiencies.

The FCA’s April 2026 review highlighted policies and procedures, CDD / EDD processes, and compliance monitoring and audit as key focus areas.

Policy Review This Policy shall be reviewed at least annually and sooner if there is: 

a material change to applicable law or regulation;



a material change to the Firm’s business or investor base;



a material change to the structure of the Funds;



a change of fund administrator or other key service provider; or



a material AML incident, control failure or regulatory issue.

Appendix 1 – Examples of Red Flags The following are examples of activity or circumstances that may require further review, escalation or enhanced due diligence. The list is illustrative and not exhaustive. A. Subscription Red Flags 

subscription monies received from an account not obviously in the name of the investor;



last-minute pressure to accept funds before full due diligence is complete;



reluctance to provide standard KYC or ownership documentation;



inconsistent information in subscription documents;



unexplained use of multiple entities, nominees or intermediaries;



subscriptions from jurisdictions not obviously connected to the investor;



unusually large seed or initial investments from a single opaque source;



sudden changes in funding arrangements without credible explanation.

B. Redemption Red Flags 

redemption shortly after subscription without a clear commercial explanation;



request to remit redemption proceeds to a new or unrelated bank account;



urgent redemption request accompanied by recent changes in account details or signatories;



redemption patterns inconsistent with the investor’s prior behaviour;



attempts to bypass standard administrator payment controls;



requests to split proceeds across multiple accounts or recipients.

C. Side Letter Red Flags 

side letter requests that obscure beneficial ownership, investor identity or payment arrangements;



side letter provisions seeking atypical confidentiality around investor identity or account details;



requests for special settlement mechanics not consistent with standard fund procedures;



requests that could impede the Firm’s or Administrator’s AML, sanctions or reporting obligations.

D. Intermediary / Introducer Red Flags 

introducer unwilling to provide sufficient information on the underlying investor;



reliance requests from intermediaries in jurisdictions with weaker AML standards;



unexplained layering of nominees, advisers or placement entities;



intermediary compensated in a manner not transparent or not obviously connected to its role;



discrepancies between information held by the intermediary and the Fund / Administrator.

E. Managed Account / Bespoke Relationship Red Flags 

pressure to alter normal onboarding standards for a strategic or anchor investor;



complex ownership or control arrangements with unclear rationale;



requests for bespoke cash or custody arrangements outside standard infrastructure;



side arrangements affecting payment flows, fees or reporting that are not fully documented;



difficulty identifying ultimate decision-makers or source of wealth.

Appendix 2 – Allocation of Responsibilities Firm The Firm is responsible for: 

maintaining its business-wide AML framework;



approving and reviewing this Policy;



appointing an MLRO, Deputy MLRO and appropriate compliance oversight;



conducting oversight of delegated AML arrangements;



reviewing exceptions, escalations and periodic administrator reporting; and



making suspicious activity decisions at Firm level where required.

Administrator The Administrator is expected to perform the AML services delegated to it under the administration agreement, which may include: 

investor onboarding;



collection and review of KYC and due diligence documentation;



sanctions, PEP and adverse media screening;



validation of investor payment details;



ongoing monitoring and refresh;



exception management; and



escalation of material AML concerns.

Funds / Governing Bodies The relevant Fund and its governing body retain such fund-level responsibilities as arise under applicable Cayman law, constitutional documents and service provider arrangements.

